vectorData.altText: 4. The dominant cell type in the fibrous layer of the periosteum is the _____________.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Thatâ€™s right! Fibrocytes are the dominant cell type in the fibrous layer of periosteum. They produce collagen type I, forming the dense irregular CT layer that is periosteum.

superficial fibrous layer is dense irregular CT: collagen type I, produced by fibrocytes, form a dense CT capsule that attaches bone to other structures, such as skeletal muscle, tendon, or ligament
2. deep cellular (osteogenic) layer: consists of osteoprogenitor cells, osteoblasts, bone-
    lining cells and osteoclasts; fxns in bone growth, repair & remodelling

On the images to the left, the dense irregular CT of the periosteum blends with the dense irregular CT of the epimysium surrounding a skeletal muscle, thus attaching muscle to bone. Collagen type I fibres of the periosteum blend with collagen type I fibres of superficial circumferential osteons and are cemented there into the bone matrix; these are called perforating or Sharpeyâ€™s fibres, and are more robust at points of ligament or tendon attachment, where tensile forces are greatest.
